Perform RFM Analysis¶

  • For Recency, Calculate the number of days between present date and date of last purchase for each customer.
  • For Frequency, Calculate the number of orders for each customer.
  • For Monetary, Calculate sum of purchase price for each customer
In [61]:
# Store a date as a reference point for recency calculations
PRESENT = dt.datetime(2011, 12, 10)

# Convert date to datetime format
uk_data['InvoiceDate'] = pd.to_datetime(uk_data['InvoiceDate'])
In [62]:
rfm= uk_data.groupby('CustomerID').agg({'InvoiceDate': lambda date: (PRESENT - date.max()).days,
                                        'InvoiceNo': lambda num: len(num),
                                        'TotalPrice': lambda price: price.sum()})
In [63]:
# Change the column names
rfm.columns=['monetary','frequency','recency']
In [64]:
rfm['recency'] = rfm['recency'].astype(int)
In [65]:
rfm['monetary'] = rfm['monetary'].astype(int)

X = rfm
In [82]:
# Choose number of Clusters using the elbow method
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
# start with 10 number of clusters
wcss = []
for i in range(2,15):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters =i, init = 'k-means++', max_iter =300, n_init =10, random_state =0)
    kmeans.fit(X)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)
    
plt.plot(range(2,15), wcss)
plt.title('The Elbow Method')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.show()
In [83]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from yellowbrick.cluster import KElbowVisualizer



model = KMeans()
visualizer = KElbowVisualizer(model, k=(2,10))



visualizer.fit(X) # Fit the data to the visualizer
visualizer.show() # Finalize and render the figure

# Choose number of Clusters using the elbow method
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
# start with 10 number of clusters
wcss = []
for i in range(2,10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters =i, init = 'k-means++', max_iter =300, n_init =10, random_state =0)
    kmeans.fit(X1)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)
plt.plot(range(2,10), wcss)
plt.title('The Elbow Method')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.show()

from sklearn import preprocessing
import math
rfm3D=rfm.copy()
rfm3D['recency'] = rfm3D['recency'].replace(0,1)
rfm3D['Recency_log'] = rfm3D['recency'].apply(math.log)
rfm3D['Frequency_log'] = rfm3D['frequency'].apply(math.log)
rfm3D['monetary'] = rfm3D['monetary'].replace(0,0.001)
rfm3D['Amount_log'] = rfm3D['monetary'].apply(math.log)
feature_vector=['Recency_log','Frequency_log','Amount_log']
X=rfm3D[feature_vector].values
scaler=preprocessing.StandardScaler()
X_scaled=scaler.fit_transform(X)

fig=plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
ax=fig.add_subplot(111,projection='3d')
xs=rfm3D.Recency_log
ys=rfm3D.Frequency_log
zs=rfm3D.Amount_log
ax.scatter(xs,ys,zs,s=5)
ax.set_xlabel('Recency')
ax.set_ylabel('Frequency')
ax.set_zlabel('Monetary value')
plt.show()
